"&#xa0;\nWritten evidence submitted by STFC WiSTEM NETWORK (WSC090) &#xa0;&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWhy do numbers of women in STEM academic careers decline further up the career ladder?\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n5.1.\n&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIn contrast to other disciplines, STEM is per\nceived as \na \nroute to demonstrating personal achievement, rather than as an endeavour which improves peoples’ lives as a whole.\n&#xa0;\n5.2.\n&#xa0;&#xa0; \nWithin \nsome \nSTEM\n fields (for example, chemistry, computational science, theoretical physics, etc.)\n, i\nndependent\n work \ntends to be \nvalued more than collaborative work\n which in turn tends to favour male \nsuccess factors\n. For example, \nU\nniversities require\n senior staff to establish and lead their own \nindependent \nresearch \ngroup\ns; individually\n-authored publications \nare a major m\neasure of ability\n.\n&#xa0;\n5.3.\n&#xa0;&#xa0; \nSTEM careers \nare often \nportrayed \nto be both \nall-consuming\n \nand overwhelmingly competitive. There is a strong preconception that \none cannot \nparticipate in science on anything other than a completely immersive basis.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n5.4.\n&#xa0;&#xa0; \nSTEM careers\n \ncharacteristically \nprogress \naccording \nto \nthe \nprestige\n built amongst peers, which is perceived to \nbe in contrast to \npreferred measures of success\n favoured by women\n.\n&#xa0;\n5.5.\n&#xa0;&#xa0; \nSTEM career progression focusses on q\nuantity \nas the \nmost important measure of productivity (e.g. number of publications, \ncitations, \nH-\nindex\n)\n which militates against career breaks or reduced working hours.\n&#xa0;\n5.6.\n&#xa0;&#xa0; \nEvaluation of \nsuccess \nin STEM jobs \ntypically \nrelies heavily on \n‘quantity’ (see above), \ntechnical \nability and intellectual rigor\n,\n \nbut \noften \nfails to \nformally \nhighlight \nand recognise \nfacets of ability which have a significant impact on actual performance\n. \nFor example, a\ncademic scientists spend a considerable \nproportion of their \ntime communicating\n (in ar\nticles, \nat conferences and seminars\n), \nnetworking, writing grant proposals, supervising students, managing staff, teaching and\n \n- \nincreasingly\n \n-\n \nperforming public outreach activities and working \non \nthe commercial exploitation of their findings. \nFailure to re\ncognise \nthe importance of \nthese overarching activities potentially \nreinforces \ngender bias.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n7.1.\n&#xa0;&#xa0; \n“I am\n not good enough for STEM”.\n \nWomen\n come to believe tha\nt they do not hav\ne the talent, skills,\n or motivation r\nequired to advance in a STEM career. They perceive their \nmale \npeers as better prepared or more motivated than they are.\n&#xa0;\n7.2.\n&#xa0;&#xa0; \n“\nSTEM is not for me”.\nWomen\n perceive that STEM career\ns\n do\n \nnot play to their strengths or \nmotivations.\n&#xa0;\n7.3.\n&#xa0;&#xa0; \n“In order to succeed in STEM, one has to sacrific\ne relationships and family”\nWomen\n f\near that a career in STEM can\nnot be reconciled with their (future) domestic life. \nIn contrast, \nW\niSTEM members are keen to emphasise \nthat \ntheir own experiences\n differ and a\nn academic STEM job \noften \noffers greater flexibility than a teaching job\n when it comes to raising \na family\n.\n&#xa0;\n7.4.\n&#xa0;&#xa0; \n“A STEM career\n requires too much commitment and \ntoo many \nsacrifices for a job with little stability in the early stages and \nrelatively low \nfinancial returns.\n”\nThe short term nature and \nneed to be \nhigh\nly\n geographical\nly mobile, particularly during \nearly\n-\ncareer\n, is a major \nobstacle highlighted by women\n, especially when contrasted with the financial rewards and stability other care\ners with such deman\nd\ns can bring in the long term.\n&#xa0;\nWhen women leave academia, what careers do they transition into? What are the consequences of scientifically trained women applying their skills in different employment sectors?\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWhat should universities and the higher education sector do to retain women grad\nuates and PhD students in academic careers? Are there examples of good practice?\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n11.1.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nRaise \ngeneral \nawareness \nthat STEM has historically been a male dominated field and that both women and men need to work towards reducing any continuing in-built bias. This might include awar\neness\n-\nraising for \nstaff\n at all levels within STEM organisations, as well as targeted training for individuals involved \nin \nrecruiting and developing staff.\n. It may be appropriate for \npeer-review processes \nto be reviewed such that any \nunconscious bias\n in ass\nessments can be removed from processes \nand \nprocedures\n. \n&#xa0;\n11.2.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nInstigate dialog\nue\n about the STEM culture and diversity and equality issues by holding high visi\nbility lectures followed by\n discussions. An example of good practice comes from the South African Institute of \nPhysics which always includes \nin its annual conference a plenary lecture on Women in Physics (this year given by a member of our network).\n&#xa0;\n11.3.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nPhD supervisors, university tuto\nrs and people managing STEM personnel should be trained to \ntake\n into account gender differences\n, for instance the Royal Society of Chemistry reports that female chemistry \nPhDs \nfind the experience to be \ntoo isolating\n.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n11.4.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nFunding bodies should \nrequire diversi\nty \ntraining \non the part of its grant recipients, \nas well as \nthe \ntraining \nof their own staff managing grant applications.\n&#xa0;\n11.5.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nWhen \nsponsoring\n conferences and other networking events, funding bodies should state that the list of invited speakers is expected to \ncomprise both men and women, and \nthat \njustification \nis required \nwhen \na suitable degree of diversity is not demonstrated.\n Funding bodies should also review the limitations on number of years since PhD for eligibility for some fellowships. This criterion sho\nuld be revised to take career breaks into account. \nFor the latter point\ns\n, an example of such good practice comes from the London Mathematical Society. \n&#xa0;\n11.6.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nPhD co\nurses should include training on\n skills necessary for career advancement such as writing \neffective \ngrant proposals\n and successful \nnetworking\n activities, \nas well \nas awareness\n-\nraising with regard to gender \nbias.\n&#xa0;\n11.7.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nSenior management and leaders of STEM organisations \nshould \nendeavour to \ndiscourage \na \nlong-\nworking-\nhours culture and promote \npositive \nw\nork/life balance for all staff. \nF\nlexible working\n arrangements for both men and \nwomen should be \npromoted wherever \nit \ncan be seen to have no \nnegative\n impact on productivity. In general, job descriptions \nshould be created that can be easily divided into part-time \n“\nchunks\n”\n that can be shared among several people. \nIdeally, there should be an aspiration for m\neetings \nto \nbe only held during core hours \nof the day, e.g. \nbetween 9:30 and 3pm\n, \nand attendance \nat \nmee\ntings (especially if international) via videolink should be routinely enabled whenever possible.\n&#xa0;\n11.8.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nSenior management and leaders of STEM organisations should endeavour to r\necognise that both women and men have responsibilities outside of work and make reaso\nnable allowances \nequally for both genders\n \nwhen this\n does not impact negatively on productivity\n over the medium timescale\n.\n \nInitiatives should encourage \nequality of caring duties.\n For example, encourage male employees to take their turn picking their childre\nn up from school and take\n time off when a child is sick\n - t\noo many schemes, such as flexible and part time working, seem to be aimed at helping women juggle and cope, but still assume that the women do more than their share of the domestic and caring \nduties. Where possible, allow both men and women to work part time on a temporary basis if there is a problem in the family, wi\nthout losing full-time status. \nEmployers should recognise the increasing need for long term care of elderly relatives will be a s\nignificant trend over the coming years and \nrecognise the need for \ngender equality \namong\n carers\n.\n&#xa0;\n11.9.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nQuantitative measures of staff and job applicants’ productivity such as number of papers published and h-\nindex\n should be replaced \nwith a comprehensive evaluati\non of the\n person’s contribution to the organi\ns\nation \nand the field\n.\n \nFor example, they should provide \nacknowledgement and credit\n \nfor tasks such as organisation of group seminars, engagement with visiting school-children, mentoring junior colleagues, taking \no\nn \nplacement students, acting as counsellors, \nto name just a few.\n&#xa0;\n11.10.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nSTEM professions should be \nmore effectively \nmarketed \nto \nboth genders. \nWhilst leading edge STEM is clearly driven by tackling \nvery difficult intellectual challenges\n, this does not mean that success is founded solely on playing on \npersonal \nambition and individual recognition, which some of our members feel to be the case.\n \nAn alternative approach might be to better emphasise STEM’s \nrole in bringing\n change\ns\n to \ns\nociety, \nhelp\ning\n solve \ng\nlobal problems and mak\ning\n people’s \nl\nives better through collaborative working and co-operation\n. \n&#xa0;\n11.11.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nWith regard to \nrecruitment\n, w\nhen preparing adverts for vacancies, the advert content and language used should appeal to both genders\n. \nIn promo\ntion and internal recruitment procedures, all eligible candidates should be actively encouraged to apply. This \nsh\nould \nhelp \ncompens\nate for the tendency of women\n not \nto \nput themselves\n \nforward\n which some of our members have witnessed\n. \nIt is the experience of many women in our network that ambition is not considered a trait that women should display or \nadmit to\n.\n \n&#xa0;\n11.12.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nPeer-reviewed STEM journals should not communicate the manuscript’s author’s names to the reviewers.\n&#xa0;\n11.13.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nIn order to counteract the lack of job stability, the employment structure of \nmany \nresearch groups should be modified. At the moment these consist of one group leader with a permanent position and a number of postdoctoral research associates (referred to a\ns postdocs) on fixed term contracts, in addition to PhD students. We propose that the role of senior postdocs should be professionalized by the creation of the permanent role of “researcher” to be associated with groups. This is the structure of research g\nroups in other Countries such as Italy where the retention of women in STEM careers is much higher.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWhat role should the Government have in encouraging the retention of women in academic STEM careers?\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n14.1.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nRequire \nthat universities\n and other employers of STEM staff \nchoose and \nset\n organi\ns\national \ntargets on \nnumbers of \nwomen at the different career stage\ns\n and on equ\nal pay\n. These targets should be made public, together with data on the number of women and pay reviews.\n&#xa0;\n14.2.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nC\nreate a national mentoring scheme where women at all career stages are paired with a women or man in a more advance\nd\n career\n \nstage\n&#xa0;\n14.3.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nO\nffer a career advi\nsing service to al\nl PhD students which\n addresses\n the issues of work/life balance\n, including real life testimonials.\n \n&#xa0;\n14.4.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nO\nffer starter grants specifically aimed at early career women researchers in STEM, and grants for students and post-docs\n,\n \nregardless of gender, \nreturning after a career break.\n&#xa0;\n14.5.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nOur political leaders should engage in a conversation with the \nn\nation about gender issues, in particular on the social and economic advantages of sharing work, domestic commitments, and caring responsi\nbilities (for children, the disabled and the elderly) more equally between men and women. \n&#xa0;\n14.6.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nEqualise the rights of women and men with respect to parental leave and make sure that the ratio between pay and childcare costs always makes it more advantageous f\nor both parents to work.\n&#xa0;\n14.7.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nLiaise with other governments, \nthe EU and organisations such as the World Economic Forum, which lists the gender issue as one of the key issues to tackle in order to improve the state of the \nw\norld.\n&#xa0;\n14.8.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nEncourage \nthe Research Councils\n and other funding bodies to support \ninterdisciplinary research on women in STEM\n, the STEM culture,\n \nand to gather statistics and \ndata especially aimed at quantifying the effects of gender bias in STEM jobs\n.\n&#xa0;\nConclusion&#xa0;&#xa0;\nSeptember 2013\nAPPENDIX 1 – STFC WiSTEM Membership&#xa0;Committee\n \nMembers and\n their Job Titles\n&#xa0;\nName\nJob Title\nOrganisation\nSarah Callaghan (Chair)\nSenior researcher and project manager\nSTFC\nBarbara Camanzi\nSTFC Futures Health and Cancer Care Theme Leader\nSTFC\nBarbara Montanari\nSenior \nScientist and Team Leader\nSTFC\nCharlotte Pascoe\nSenior Data Scientist\nSTFC\nHanna Fikremariam \nProject Engineer\nSTFC\nRosie Sherry\nHead of People Development\nSTFC\nSteph Tomlinson\nChartered Mechanical Engineer\nSTFC\nSarah Beardsley\nProject Manager (Space \nElectronics)\nSTFC\nYanling Ma\nMechanical Engineer\nSTFC\n&#xa0;\nWe currently have \n153\n \nmembers, whose professional roles include:\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n \n“Why So Slow? The Advancement of Women” Virginia Valian, MIT Press, 1999\n \nhttp://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H-index\n \nhttp://www.mckinsey.com/Client_Service/Organization/Latest_thinking/Unlocking_the_full_potential.aspx\n \nHeilman, Madeline E.; Wallen, Aaron S.; Fuchs, Daniella; Tamkins, Melinda M. Penalties fo\nr Success: Reactions to Women Who Succeed at Male Gender-Typed Tasks.Journal of Applied Psychology, Vol 89(3), Jun 2004, 416-427. doi: 10.1037/0021-9010.89.3.416\n Royal Society of Chemistry report “The Chemistry PhD: the Impact on Women’s Retention”, 2008\n \nhttp://www.rsc.org/ima\ng\nes/womensreten\nt\nion_tcm18-139215.pdf\n  \n “Is there equality in the way we communicate?” Event organised by the IOP Physics Communicators Group and the IOP Wom\nen in Physics Group, 21\nst\n June 2013,  \nhttp://www.iopblog.org/gender-and-science-communication/\n Anna Fels, “Do Women Lack Ambition?”, Harvard Business Review, Apr 01, 2004. \n \nhttp://www.wisecampaign.org.uk/news/2011/02/diversity-award-recognises-that-gender-is-no-barrier-to-stfc-science\n \nhttp://www.stfc.ac.uk/resources/pdf/STFCWiS.pdf\n"